In [7]:
def doKFold(X,Y,k,c,ker):
    kf = KFold(n_splits=k)
    acc = 0
    model = svm.SVC(C = c,kernel = ker)
    for train_index, test_index in kf.split(X):
        X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
        Y_train, Y_test = Y[train_index], Y[test_index]
        model.fit(X_train, Y_train)
        acc += model.score(X_test,Y_test)
    return acc/k

C = np.arange(0.1,10,0.5)
hyp_par = ["linear","poly","rbf"]
chosen_hyp_par = []

for val in TV_array:
    bc = 0
    bhyp = ""
    bacc = -1
    for c in C:
        for ker in hyp_par:
            acc = doKFold(val[1],val[3],10,c,ker)
            if acc > bacc:
                bacc = acc
                bhyp = ker
                bc = c
    chosen_hyp_par.append([bc,bhyp])

def doKFold_all(X,Y,k,c,ker):
    kf = KFold(n_splits=k)
    acc = []
    model = svm.SVC(C = c,kernel = ker)
    for train_index, test_index in kf.split(X):
        X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
        Y_train, Y_test = Y[train_index], Y[test_index]
        model.fit(X_train, Y_train)
        acc.append(model.score(X_test,Y_test))
    return acc

accuracies = []
for i in range(3):
    val = TV_array[i]
    c = chosen_hyp_par[i][0]
    ker = chosen_hyp_par[i][1]
    accuracies.append(doKFold_all(val[0],val[2],10,c,ker))

def maxindex(t):
    if type(t) != np.ndarray:
        return (t,t > 0)
    else:
        i = 0
        maxi = t[0]
        for j in range(1,3):
            if t[j] > maxi:
                i = j
                maxi = t[j]
        return (maxi,i)


for k in range(3):
    clf = svm.SVC(kernel=chosen_hyp_par[k][1], C=chosen_hyp_par[k][0])
    clf.fit(TV_array[k][0], TV_array[k][2])

    plt.figure()
    plt.clf()
    plt.scatter(TV_array[k][0][:, 0], TV_array[k][0][:, 1], c=TV_array[k][2], zorder=10, cmap=plt.cm.Paired,
                edgecolor='k', s=20)

    # Circle out the test data
    plt.scatter(TV_array[k][1][:, 0], TV_array[k][1][:, 1], s=80, facecolors='none',
                zorder=10, edgecolor='k')

    plt.axis('tight')
    x_min = TV_array[k][0][:, 0].min()
    x_max = TV_array[k][0][:, 0].max()
    y_min = TV_array[k][0][:, 1].min()
    y_max = TV_array[k][0][:, 1].max()

    XX, YY = np.mgrid[x_min:x_max:200j, y_min:y_max:200j]
    Z = clf.decision_function(np.c_[XX.ravel(), YY.ravel()])
    
    # Put the result into a color plot
    Zm = [maxindex(z) for z in Z ]
    Z = np.array([z[0] for z in Zm])
    Zm = np.array([z[1] for z in Zm])
    Z = Z.reshape(XX.shape)
    Zm = Zm.reshape(XX.shape)
    plt.pcolormesh(XX, YY, Zm, cmap=plt.cm.Paired)
    plt.contour(XX, YY, Z, colors=['k', 'k', 'k'],
                linestyles=['--', '-', '--'], levels=[-.5, 0, .5])

    plt.title(chosen_hyp_par[k][1])
plt.show()

The support vectors are the data points which define the decision boundary.

That is why a SVM is very light because all points which are not support vectors can be forgotten for the decision process.

They are the points which maximize the margin.

The optimal parameters for the simulated data are :

- kernel "rbf" and C = 2.1 for the two gaussians mixture
- kernel "linear" and C = 0.1 for the 3 blops
- kernel "rbf" and C = 0.6 for the two moons

The optimal parameters for the Diabetic Retinopathy Dataset are kernel "linear" and C =0.1.

Some kernels are better than others depending on the actual separabality of the data. For exemple if the the data is linearly separable then a linear kernel will perfectly do the job. Eventually the data points are not perfectly separated or the separation is of another shape then the kernel which best transforms the data will work better.
